Still stronger testimony to its importance is given by the constant references to it in the Digest ; and the numerous commenta of the jurists on its provisions ¹, which have rendered possible such restora- tions of it as have been made.

The laws of Rome, probably from a very early period, had encouraged marriage and the rearing of children, and discouraged celibacy². The censor was himself probably required by old law to be a married man ⁸, and was entitled to question citizens as to their condition, and to levy a fine (‘ uxorium ¹) from the unmarried‘.

The attention of the dictator Caesar had been called to the need of fresh legislation in this direction by the revelation in the census-lists of the ravages which the civil wars had made in the populati0n⁸; which he endeavoured to meet by offering valuable rewards to the fathers of many children ⁶.
